title: Braised Monkfish with Wild Mushrooms and Cipollini Onions
summary: Braised Monkfish with Wild Mushrooms and Cipollini Onions is a gluten free, primal, and pescatarian recipe with 4 servings. One serving contains 735 calories, 44g of protein, and 39g of fat. For $11.98 per serving, this recipe covers 38% of your daily requirements of vitamins and minerals. 2 people have made this recipe and would make it again. From preparation to the plate, this recipe takes around 45 minutes. Not a lot of people really liked this main course. Head to the store and pick up coarse salt and pepper, fennel seeds, rosemary, and a few other things to make it today. To use up the balsamic vinegar you could follow this main course with the Skinny Strawberry Ice Cream as a dessert. All things considered, we decided this recipe deserves a spoonacular score of 76%. This score is good. Similar recipes include Braised beef with red onions & wild mushrooms, Braised Lentils with Cipollini Onions, and Creamed Cipollini Onions and Mushrooms.

winePairing.pairingText: Fish works really well with Pinot Grigio, Gruener Veltliner, and Pinot Noir. Fish is as diverse as wine, so it's hard to pick wines that go with every fish. A crisp white wine, such as a pinot grigio or Grüner Veltliner, will suit any delicately flavored white fish. Meaty, strongly flavored fish such as salmon and tuna can even handle a light red wine, such as a pinot noir. The Chloe Pinot Grigio with a 4.2 out of 5 star rating seems like a good match. It costs about 13 dollars per bottle.
